rmk:
continuation from XC351439:
The Tit sings 5 other types of verses (Strophentypen nach Bergmann) with changing motives, rhythm and pitches (Tonhöhen)
4 – fourth type of verse: 50 verses,  to 5:27, each verse with nearly the same motive 3-9 times repeated (mostly, 23x, 6 times)  
5 – fifth type of verse : 66 verses, from 5:21 to 11:24, each verse with the same motive, which is similar to a Coal Tit's song,   1- 9 times repeated (mostly, 29x, 6 times)
6 – sixth type of verse: from 11:25 to 11:50, only 3 verses  
7 – seventh type of verse: from 12:02 to 12:14, only 4 verses. At 12:11 only one motive, similar to the second type (in XC351439)
12:15 alarm call
8 – eigth type of verse: from 12:20 to 12:52, each verse with nearly the same motive, 7 times repeated.
From 5:28 a second Great Tit in the background begins to answer.
At least the Tit flies into a garden with a lot of trees, where I cannot see it all the time, so I am not sure, if the last 3 types of verses have been sung by one individuum, or,  if one ore two types have been sung from a second individuum, coming into the foreground.

rmk:
A recording of drumming which is not commonly heard. There is also some tapping at 0:19.

I heard the bird drum on an old tree and I started recording. 
As I looked into the tree I saw a green woodpecker low down in the crown. However, when the drumming sounded again (1:30) I could see that it was not this bird drumming. Another green woodpecker came and sat in the top of the tree and the lower one flew off (1:59). 
I think the upper one flew off too. At 2:16 I heard the bird perform the more typical "yaffle" which surprised me as at this stage I could not see any green woodpeckers. I took a few steps forward and stopped the recording. The green woodpecker that had drummed and called flew out of a nest hole in the tree and flew to some others nearby!
The bird then performed a number of yaffles which I captured in recording XC553921. 

As I understand it, the drumming is performed, not as a territorial song (as is the case with Greater Spotted Woodpeckers which drum often), but is given when the male and female are present at the nest. I am unsure whether the presence of a third bird had any bearing on the bird drumming.

Recorded with an Olympus LS-12 and Sennheiser ME66 handheld. Edited below 300 Hz to remove wind noise.

rmk:
Pareja de cárabos cantando a dúo, emitiendo los mismos tonos macho y hembra, ya fuera de la época de reproducción. Estaban en los árboles de ribera que crecen a las orillas del río Guadalquivir. Nótese como no cantan realmente a dúo, en el sentido de responderse el uno al otro, si no que hembra y macho tienen su propio ritmo de canto y pausas, parece que de forma independiente el uno del otro, llegando unas veces a cantar a la vez, para luego ir desfasando de nuevo. Por tanto parece que los dos emiten ese canto dirigido a otras parejas, quizás estableciendo su territorio, más que una comunicación entre ambos.

  Pair of tawny owls singing in duet, making the same tones, both male and female, out of the breeding season. They were perching in the riverbank trees of Guadalquivir river. Note here they don't sing really in a duet, in the sense of replying one another, but male and female have their own rhythm of tones and pauses independently, so they can reach a moment in which they sing at the same times, and after a few calls they mismatch again. Therefore it should be more correct to think they sing for their territory, sending a message to other pairs, instead of being a communication between them.

file-name: XC348092-Heb Wren song XC SY 1,3,5,4,3,4 C'bay phone-box BIRD, 16 April 15.mp3
rmk: Song from a Hebridean Wren (T t hebridensis) recorded at Castle Bay, Barra, Outer Hebrides. As is typical for Wrens proclaiming territorial rights, this singer sang from a variety of prominent positions that, presumably, marked out its territory. Each time it sang it stuck to a similar theme but as it shifted around it slightly changed the mix of trills. Basically, you could say that it sang one composition at A, a slightly different composition at B, another at C (and so on). Because Hebridean Wren is stated to utter just one or two trills, I decided to count the number of 'trills-per-phrase'. I discovered that the number of trills often was around three, four or (less often) five. This clip contains a segment of song whose 'trill count' per phrase is as follows. First phrase: 1 trill 0:01 (note that this first trill was probably aborted - a frequent occurrence when a bird is edgy); second phrase 0:10, 3 trills; third phrase 0:21, 5 trills; fourth phrase 0:32, 4 trills; fifth phrase 0:42, 3 trills; sixth phrase 0:51, 4 trills. A full account of the vocalisations of Hebridean Wren versus Wren is here: XC347739

rmk: This male Blackbird developped during springtime strophes with a remarkable loud sound leap (Tonsprung), just before he ended with an even higher pitched squiggel. Therefore we call him "Kikeriki-Amsel" (cock-a-doodle-doo-Blackbird). At the moment he still sings this strophes sometimes very early in the morning. When I took this recording, he sat for a long time on a crest, at the blind end of Kleinfeld.

file-name: XC349569-3)  MISTELDROSSEL,  Düdüdü-Reihung  1.05.2009   HhW N  8_38  (mini-disc)  gült. l.    .mp3
rmk:
First in 2008 I heard this Mistle Thrush with its „endless“ sequences of a very special düdüdü-motive, very loudly and powerful. Look at my first note in XC187615.. 
In the following years soon this motive was introduced in other Mistle Thrush songs in this wood, often not as clear as in the songs of the Mistle Thrush I heard first, and since 2012 the long düdüdü-sequences of the first years were over. In 2015 the düdüdü-motive completely seemed to be gone. But in 2016 it was back and to be heard in its old powerful loudlyness in the songs of at least two Mistle Thrushs in the north and south area of the wood. If one of them still is the same individuum as in first time, I can't decide, specially because even in the first years in the course of springtime the long sequences were shortened. Now I put 25 recordings into xeno-canto to show the development of this extravagant motive over the time of nine seasons.

In the following years soon this motive was introduced into other Mistle Thrushs songs in this wood, often not as clear as in the songs of the Mistle Thrush I heard first, and since 2012 the long düdüdü-sequences of the first years were over. In 2015 the düdüdü-motive completely seemed to be gone.
But in 2016 it was back and to be heard in its old powerful loudlyness in the songs of at least two Mistle Thrushs in the north and south area of the wood. If one of them still is the same individuum as in first time, I can't decide, specially because even in the first years in the course of springtime the long sequences were shortened.
 I now put 24 recordings into xeno-canto to show the development of this extravagant motive over the time of nine seasons.

Singing from the top of a fir, in cloudy and lightly raining weather on a silent Sunday morning. Same location as XC468201 but today fewer background species, for example no song thrush or blackbird (as far as I can hear). Recorded from rather close with Telinga Pro V and Stereo DAT microphone. No filtering, but at 1:28 forty seconds have been cut out because of noise from a passing airplane. The remaining "noise" is a nearby creek.

For a video of the same bird on the same day's (sunny) evening, see <https://vimeo.com/332999078>.
